*THF Unit* The A&AT LLC LaPorte facility complies with OSHA Standard 29 CFR 1910.119, Process Safety Management of highly hazardous chemicals, and has applied the programs and policies found in the standard to activities throughout the entire plant.



Specific program elements include:



1. Employee Participation - It is the policy of A&AT LLC LaPorte to seek participation of employees at all levels in establishing procedures and practices that govern Health, Safety and Environmental issues.  The PSM Manual Employee Participation element #PSM-001 outlines this process;

2. Process Safety Information - Process safety information is maintained for each operating area.  The PSM Manual Process Safety Information element #PSM-002 outlines this process;

3. Process Hazard Analysis - A detailed hazard assessment, using the HAZOP and WHAT-if/Checklist methodologies, is conducted on all processes to insure that they have been designed safely.  The process also includes a Layer of Protection analysis; 

4. Operating Procedures - A system is in place to ensure that updated and approved procedures cover all aspects of process unit operation;

5. Training - A training program has been established to ensure that all personnel are well trained in the specific duties of their jobs (The process also includes an annual Training Needs Analysis);

6. Contractors - It is A&AT LLC LaPorte's objective to partner with contractors that share the same safety philosophy.  A dedicated, collective, and consistent approach by A&AT LLC LaPorte and contractors will enhance and maintain the safety and health of our respective employees.  The PSM Contractor Management Program element #PSM-006 outlines this process;

7. Prestartup Safety Review - A prestartup safety review walk down and checklist is completed for each managed change that significantly impacts the Process Safety Information.  The PSM Manual MOC/PSSR element #PSM-010 outlines this process; 

8. Mechanical Integrity - An equipment inspection program is in place to ensure equipment remains in good condition to prevent releases;

9. Hot Work Permits - A work permit system is in place to ensure that all work on process equipment and all hot work are conducted in a safe manner.  The Safe Work Permit Procedure; SAF-002 (resides in the Site's Safety Manual) outlines this process;

10. Management of Change - A management of change system has been established and implemented to ensure that any change is thoroughly reviewed prior to implementation.  The PSM Manual Management of Change element #PSM-010 outlines this process; 

11. Incident Investigation - Incidents are investigated using one of several industry recognized methodologies, such as Fishbone, to determine system level root causes that can be remedied to prevent a reoccurrence. Employees and contractors involved in the incident are included on the investigation team.  The PSM Manual Incident Investigation element #PSM-011 outlines this process; 

12. Emergency Planning and Response - An emergency action plan has been established for the entire plant including procedures for handling small releases of chemicals.  The plan is known as the One Plan and is a stand-alone document;  

13. Compliance Audits - Programs are audited annually; at least every three years through PSM compliance audits; every three years through an internal corporate review; and weekly safety inspections of the facility are conducted by cross functional teams.  Action items resulting from these are tracked to a timely completion; 

14. Trade Secrets - Access by employees to information has few restrictions. Contractors access to information is managed based on their involvement in PSM and the day to day activities of the plant.
